  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>The <strong>local pack</strong> is a Google Search feature that displays a map alongside three business listings for location-based queries. It appears above organic results for searches like "plumber near me" or "dentist in Chicago," and captures approximately 42% of all local search clicks. Rankings are determined by three factors: relevance, distance, and prominence.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Click share</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~42% of local clicks</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Listings shown</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3 businesses</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The local pack replaced the seven-listing "7-pack" in August 2015. The reduction from seven to three made each position dramatically more valuable — and more competitive. For most local service businesses, winning a spot is the highest-ROI SEO achievement available.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is the local pack?</h2>
        <p>The local pack is the boxed section in Google search results containing a map and three business listings that appears for location-based queries. Each listing shows the business name, star rating, review count, business category, address, hours, and sometimes photos or attribute badges like "Women-owned" or "Free estimates."</p>
        <p>Google also refers to it as the "Map Pack," "3-Pack," or "Local Results." The format replaced the previous seven-listing structure in August 2015. According to BrightLocal's 2025 Local Consumer Survey, 98% of consumers searched online for a local business in the past year — the local pack is the first thing they see for most of those searches.</p>
        <p>The data in each listing comes directly from your Google Business Profile (GBP). If your GBP has incomplete or incorrect information, that's what searchers see in the pack.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's three ranking factors</div>
          <p>Google has publicly confirmed that local pack rankings depend on three signals: <strong>Relevance</strong> (how well your GBP matches the query), <strong>Distance</strong> (proximity to the searcher), and <strong>Prominence</strong> (reviews, citations, backlinks, and overall web presence). All three must be strong to compete in contested markets.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why the local pack matters for local businesses</h2>
        <p>Four reasons the local pack is worth dedicating SEO resources to:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Position zero visibility.</strong> The local pack appears above organic results, which means local pack position #3 is more visible than organic position #1 for the same query. It's the first thing most local searchers see.</li>
          <li><strong>42% click capture.</strong> Nearly half of all local search clicks go into the local pack — not to paid ads, not to organic results. Three businesses divide this pool among themselves.</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile dominance.</strong> Over 60% of local searches happen on mobile. On a phone screen, the local pack fills the entire first view — organic results don't appear without scrolling.</li>
          <li><strong>Direct conversion paths.</strong> Local pack listings include buttons to call, get directions, or visit the website. A searcher can become a phone call without ever clicking through to your website.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How the local pack ranking algorithm works</h2>

        <h3>Relevance — what you control most</h3>
        <p>Relevance measures how well your Google Business Profile matches the search query. This is the factor you have the most control over. Key signals:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Primary GBP category</strong> — the single most important individual local ranking factor. Choosing "Personal Injury Attorney" vs "Lawyer" can be the difference between appearing in the pack or not.</li>
          <li>Secondary categories, listed services, and business description</li>
          <li>Profile completeness — incomplete profiles rarely make the 3-Pack</li>
          <li>GBP posts and Q&A activity (signals an active, current business)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Distance — what you cannot optimize away</h3>
        <p>Distance measures the proximity of your business to the searcher. Google uses GPS on mobile and IP location on desktop. You cannot move your address, but you can optimize service area settings in your GBP to indicate the geographic range your business covers beyond your physical location.</p>
        <p>Distance is the one local pack ranking factor that cannot be fully overcome through optimization. A business 20 miles away with excellent optimization will sometimes lose to a nearby business with average optimization simply because of proximity.</p>

        <h3>Prominence — what you build over time</h3>
        <p>Prominence measures how well-known and trusted your business is online. It's the hardest factor to build quickly but the one that compounds most over time:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Google Review count, average rating, and velocity (new reviews per month)</li>
          <li>Citation consistency (NAP matching across directories)</li>
          <li>Backlinks from locally relevant websites</li>
          <li>Brand mentions and overall web presence</li>
          <li>Your website's authority and local content quality</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Types of local pack results</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
