        <h2 id="examples">Real local pack examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — HVAC company breaks into the 3-Pack</h3>
        <p>An HVAC company in Phoenix wasn't appearing for "AC repair Phoenix." Audit revealed their primary GBP category was set to "Air Conditioning Repair Service" instead of "HVAC contractor." After correcting the primary category, posting weekly GBP updates, and responding to all Google Reviews, they reached position #3 within 90 days — adding 40+ monthly calls directly from the local pack.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — Law firm loses local pack position to proximity</h3>
        <p>A personal injury firm in Dallas held the #1 local pack spot for two years. A competitor opened a new office closer to downtown Dallas and aggressively optimized their GBP. The proximity advantage pushed the original firm out of the top three. This illustrates the one factor that cannot be overcome: if a better-optimized competitor is significantly closer to searchers, distance wins.</p>

        <h3>Example 3 — Multi-location restaurant chain</h3>
        <p>A taco chain with eight Houston locations created separate GBP listings for each location, each with unique location-specific photos, local reviews, and weekly GBP posts. Five of eight locations consistently appear in local pack results for "tacos near me" in their respective neighborhoods. The lesson: treat each location as its own local business, not as a branch of a chain.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local pack vs organic results — key differences</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Local pack strengths</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Above organic — position zero for local queries</li>
              <li>Direct call/directions without website visit</li>
              <li>42% click share — the biggest slice of local traffic</li>
              <li>Faster to achieve initial results (60-90 days)</li>
              <li>Mobile-first — fills the first screen on phones</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Local pack limitations</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Only 3 slots available per query</li>
              <li>Requires a verified GBP listing</li>
              <li>Proximity-dependent — location matters heavily</li>
              <li>Doesn't appear for informational queries</li>
              <li>Rankings shift based on searcher's exact location</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 best practices for local pack rankings</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Claim and fully complete your Google Business Profile.</strong> Fill every field: primary category, secondary categories, services, attributes, hours, description, and photos. Incomplete profiles rarely reach the 3-Pack.</li>
          <li><strong>Select the most specific primary category.</strong> "Dentist" outperforms "Healthcare Provider." "Personal Injury Attorney" outperforms "Lawyer." The primary category is the single highest-impact individual factor you control.</li>
          <li><strong>Build review velocity consistently.</strong> Businesses in competitive local packs average 80+ reviews. More importantly, they get 5-10 new reviews monthly. A one-time push to 50 reviews then stopping performs worse than steady 5 per month ongoing.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to all reviews.</strong> Owner response rate is a GBP signal. Respond to positive and negative reviews within 48 hours. Google can see response velocity and quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep NAP data perfectly consistent.</strong> Name, address, and phone number must match exactly across your GBP, website, and all citations. Small discrepancies (St vs Street, suite numbers) confuse Google's geographic data model.</li>
          <li><strong>Post to your GBP weekly.</strong> Regular GBP posts signal an active business. Posts can be service highlights, offers, events, or Q&A content — frequency matters more than post perfection.</li>
          <li><strong>Add photos consistently.</strong> Listings with photos get 42% more requests for directions and 35% more website clicks, per Google's own data. Add 3-5 new photos monthly.</li>
          <li><strong>Build local website content.</strong> Your website's prominence signal feeds into the local pack. Local landing pages and local blog content strengthen the prominence component over time.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — optimizing once and stopping</div>
          <p>Many businesses claim their GBP, fill it out, and never touch it again. Google's algorithm rewards active profiles. A competitor who posts weekly, gets 5+ reviews monthly, and responds to every review will outrank a better-established business that's been inactive for six months. Local pack optimization is a continuous process, not a one-time setup.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common local pack mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Wrong primary GBP category</strong> — the most common ranking mistake. Audit yours against the categories your best-ranking competitors use.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring review velocity</strong> — getting 100 reviews then stopping is worse than a steady 8 per month. Recency signals matter as much as volume.</li>
          <li><strong>NAP inconsistencies across citations</strong> — a phone number formatted differently on Yelp vs your website vs your GBP creates data confusion. Audit and standardize.</li>
          <li><strong>No GBP posts</strong> — an inactive GBP signals a potentially closed or unattended business. Google factors activity into prominence scoring.</li>
          <li><strong>Buying fake reviews</strong> — Google detects fake review patterns. A single manual action for fake reviews can remove your GBP from the pack entirely and trigger a review suspension.</li>
          <li><strong>Using a virtual office address</strong> — Google prohibits GBP listings at virtual offices and co-working spaces unless you genuinely staff the location during business hours. Detected violations result in listing suspension.</li>
        </ul>

